  "articleSummary": "The article argues that JSONB in PostgreSQL is a useful tool for storing semi‑structured data—such as webhook payloads, logs, user settings, or LLM configuration objects—but it becomes a source of technical debt when teams use it as a shortcut for undefined schemas and then treat the blob as primary business data. It illustrates a common pattern: a JSONB column is added to avoid early schema decisions, later proliferates into many inconsistent versions, forces application‑side validation, and incurs costly full‑table scans or complex indexing. The piece distinguishes legitimate use cases (write‑heavy, whole‑document fetches, or truly variable schemas) from misuse (frequent relational queries on nested fields), and recommends a hybrid approach that keeps stable columns for searchable attributes while reserving JSONB for truly flexible payloads. The tone is a pragmatic rant‑turned analysis aimed at developers, architects, and DBAs who design PostgreSQL schemas.",
